            <p>Τόπος Σαμώη υἱοῦ <lb/>Χολβιδια. <sic>Ἰρήνη</sic> τῷ <lb/>Ιστραήλ <foreign xml:lang="heb">שלום</foreign>.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="iopp0005.translation"
              corresp="#iopp0005.diplomatic #iopp0005.transcription">
            <p>This is the tomb of Samoes son of Cholbidia(?). Peace on Israel. Peace.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>White limestone Jewish tombstone from Ioppe. The inscription is recorded largely in Greek, with one final Hebrew word. The editor notes that the Greek letters are well carved, while the Hebrew letters are not skillfully done. Though the stone is fractured on its left side, the inscription is complete. The name Sameoes is of Semitic origin, representing the biblical name Shamua. The name Cholbidias seems to have no exact parallel, but that it might be either an Egyptian name or an expanded (and possibly Hellenized) form of the name Caleb. Finally, the form Ιστραήλ is attested in many different works from both the East and the West during that time period, and reflects the pronunciation of the name at that time. The editor notes that the closing formula is widely attested in both Epitaphs and synagogue inscriptions. The final word, Shalom, is recorded in Hebrew. The inscription makes use of lunate sigmas as well as large minuscule omegas in place of their majuscule counterpart.</p>
         </div>
